Those endless Toils , which always grow anew , And the poor Thresher's destined to
each our Task he readily divides
to prove Whether with just Exactness it will move : That once secure , we swiftly whirl them round ; From the strong Planks our Crabtree Staves rebound , And echoing Barns return the rattling Sound
Whether with just Exactness it will move : That once secure , we swiftly whirl them round ; From the strong Planks our Crabtree Staves rebound , And echoing Barns return the rattling Sound
Down one , one up , so well they keep the Time , The CYCLOPS' Hammers could not truer chime
with equal Force descend from high
Nor yet , the tedious Labour to beguile , And make the passing Minutes sweetly smile , Can we , like Shepherd's
what pleasing thing , Here , to the Mind

It's all a gloomy , melancholy Scene , Fit only to provoke the Muse's Spleen
The Sweat , the Dust , and suffocating Smoke ,
a new : A new , indeed , but frequently a worse !
in our Hands we wish our noisy Tools
the hated Names of Rogues and Fools
the happy Season may be fair
Prologue to the Day , We rise , admonished by his early Lay
Has bathed his panting Sides in briny Sweat
to sustain , He measures back the Hills and Dales with Pain
we stay , Got to the Door
The tattling Crowd can scarce their Garments gain , Before descends the thick impetuous Rain
the Sun , Turned once or twice
our Master calls us forth again
look again , with a more tender Eye , To think how soon it must in Ruin lie

those who feast at Ease on dainty Fare , Pity the Reapers , who their Feasts prepare
what a painful Life we daily lead ; Each Morning early rise
go late to Bed : Nor , when asleep , are we secure from Pain
the Cheat , When the same Toils we must again repeat ; To the same Barns must back again return , To labour there for Room for next Year's Corn

Like SISYPHUS , our Work is never done ; Continually rolls back the restless Stone
